Cindy Sheehan, a grieving mother who lost her son in Iraq, demands answers from President Bush.
She questions the purpose of the war and the needless loss of lives.
She believes in completing the mission but wants the troops home soon.
She has become a symbol of the anti-war movement, drawing support nationwide.
Despite facing resistance, she remains steadfast in her protest near Bush's ranch.
She seeks accountability and a second meeting with the president to express her grievances.
She embodies the pain and frustration of families who have sacrificed in the war.
